sec.p:
The value of WX*(nj) depends on the parameters of the restraint potential adopted in the FEP calculation, i.e. the reference positions of the ligands in the bound state {RX*(1j),…,RX*(nj)} and the magnitude of force constants {kX(1j),…,kX(nj)}. By minimizing the contribution of the restraint potential to the binding free-energy WX*(nj), Roux and coworkers [45] devised optimum choices for the parameters




{RX*(1j)=⟨RX(1j)⟩,…,RX*(nj)=⟨RX(nj)⟩}



and




{kX(1j)=3β-1⟨[δRX(1j)]2⟩,…,kX(nj)=3β-1⟨[δRX(nj)]2⟩}

in which, ⟨RX(1j)⟩,…,⟨RX(nj)⟩ and ⟨[δRX(1j)]2⟩,…,⟨[δRX(nj)]2⟩ are respectively the equilibrium average positions for each of the nj bound ligands at site j and their corresponding mean-square fluctuations when interacting to structure X. Here, these parameters were estimated from the space of docking solutions and the resulting force constants, in the range of 0.03 to 1.35 kcal/mol/Å2, were considered for computations of the bound state.
